{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538161"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:25:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16153"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16153"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.14,0.33,0.35,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64145"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8844"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"913"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4699"},{"type":"tags","id":"4724"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11109"},{"type":"tags","id":"11432"},{"type":"tags","id":"11515"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64145"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice. Her partner of two years was recently diagnosed with chronic hepatitis C infection. It is presumed to be vertical transmission as his mother was hepatitis C positive and he has no other risk factors. He plans to receive treatment, but she wants to know what precautions they should take until his treatment is complete. She has no significant medical history and has an etonogestrel implant for contraception. Both she and her partner have tested negative for HIV. They are in a monogamous relationship and have unprotected oral and vaginal intercourse. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding prevention of hepatitis C transmission?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence pre-exposure prophylaxis","Abstain from sexual activity until partner completes treatment","No specific precautions needed for sexual activity","Mandatory condom use for all sexual encounters","Immunisation against hepatitis C"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario addresses the risk of hepatitis C virus (HCV) transmission in a monogamous heterosexual relationship. The risk of sexual transmission of HCV is very low, with studies showing transmission rates of less than 1% per year with receptive vaginal intercourse. The risk is higher for people having anal intercourse, men who have sex with men, and people who have HIV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo specific precautions needed for sexual activity\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate advice in this situation. Importantly, her partner does not have any other risk factors for other blood-borne virus transmission which would warrant recommending condom use. The risk of sexual transmission of HCV for this couple is extremely low, and guidelines do not recommend condom use. However, the patient may wish to use barrier protection to further reduce the risk of transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbstaining from sexual activity\u003C/strong\u003E until the partner completes treatment is unnecessarily restrictive given the low risk of transmission. Treatment duration can be up to 12 weeks, and testing for sustained virological response at 12 weeks following completion of treatment would be required before treatment is considered successful. This advice could negatively impact the couple\u0027s relationship without providing significant benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMandatory condom use\u003C/strong\u003E for all sexual encounters is an option; however, it is not currently recommended by Australian and international guidelines. While couples may choose to use condoms, they should be informed that the risk of transmission through sexual contact is very low.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmunisation against hepatitis C\u003C/strong\u003E is not currently possible as no vaccination has been developed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-exposure prophylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E is not available or indicated for hepatitis C prevention. This medication is used for HIV prevention and would not protect against HCV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that the risk of sexual transmission increases in certain circumstances, such as HIV co-infection, anal sex, the presence of other sexually transmitted infections, or having multiple sexual partners. Couples should be advised to avoid sharing personal items that might have blood contact, such as razors or toothbrushes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sexual transmission of hepatitis C virus is rare, occurring in less than 1% of monogamous heterosexual relationships per year.","Barrier protection during sexual activity can further reduce the risk of transmission but is not mandatory for monogamous heterosexual couples where one partner has hepatitis C.","The risk of hepatitis C transmission increases with HIV co-infection, multiple sexual partners, and presence of other sexually transmitted infections."],"references":["Terrault NA, Dodge JL, Murphy EL, Tavis JE, Kiss A, Levin TR, Gish RG, Busch MP, Reingold AL, Alter MJ. Sexual transmission of hepatitis C virus among monogamous heterosexual couples: the HCV partners study. Hepatology. 2013 Mar;57(3):881-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23175457/","Rooney G, Gilson RJ. Sexual transmission of hepatitis C virus infection. Sex Transm Infect. 1998 Dec;74(6):399-404. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10195047/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49577"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16153"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49577"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T02:25:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T02:27:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8844"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64145"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"s